<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Alternative_Modules"
>Alternative Modules</a></h2>

<p><a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> is not the only <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3AProcessing" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Processing</a> module available on CPAN (far from it!).</p>

<p>The main alternative I would recommend is <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>.</p>

<p>Here is a quick comparison of the 2 modules:</p>

<p><a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>, actually <code>libxml2</code> on which it is based, sticks to the standards, and implements a good number of them in a rather strict way: XML, XPath, DOM, RelaxNG, I must be forgetting a couple (XInclude?). It is fast and rather frugal memory-wise.</p>

<p><a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> is older: when I started writing it <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3AParser" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Parser</a>/expat was the only game in town. It implements XML and that&#39;s about it (plus a subset of XPath, and you can use <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ATwig%3A%3AXPath" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig::XPath</a> if you have <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3AXPathEngine" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::XPathEngine</a> installed for full support). It is slower and requires more memory for a full tree than <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>. On the plus side (yes, there is a plus side!) it lets you process a big document in chunks, and thus let you tackle documents that couldn&#39;t be loaded in memory by <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>, and it offers a lot (and I mean a LOT!) of higher-level methods, for everything, from adding structure to &#34;low-level&#34; XML, to shortcuts for XHTML conversions and more. It also DWIMs quite a bit, getting comments and non-significant whitespaces out of the way but preserving them in the output for example. As it does not stick to the DOM, is also usually leads to shorter code than in <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>.</p>

<p>Beyond the pure features of the 2 modules, <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a> seems to be prefered by &#34;XML-purists&#34;, while <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> seems to be more used by Perl Hackers who have to deal with XML. As you have noted, <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> also comes with quite a lot of docs, but I am sure if you ask for help about <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a> here or on Perlmonks you will get answers.</p>

<p>Note that it is actually quite hard for me to compare the 2 modules: on one hand I know <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> inside-out and I can get it to do pretty much anything I need to (or I improve it ;--), while I have a very basic knowledge of <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a>. So feature-wise, I&#39;d rather use <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> ;--). On the other hand, I am painfully aware of some of the deficiencies, potential bugs and plain ugly code that lurk in <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a>, even though you are unlikely to be affected by them (unless for example you need to change the DTD of a document programatically), while I haven&#39;t looked much into <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3ALibXML" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::LibXML</a> so it still looks shinny and clean to me.</p>

<p>That said, if you need to process a document that is too big to fit memory and <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> is too slow for you, my reluctant advice would be to use &#34;bare&#34; <a href="/perldoc?XML%3A%3AParser" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Parser</a>. It won&#39;t be as easy to use as <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a>: basically with <a href="/~mirod/XML-Twig-3.39/Twig_pm.slow" class="podlinkpod"
>XML::Twig</a> you trade some speed (depending on what you do from a factor 3 to... none) for ease-of-use, but it will be easier IMHO than using SAX (albeit not standard), and at this point a LOT faster (see the last test in <a href="http://www.xmltwig.com/article/simple_benchmark/" class="podlinkurl"
>http://www.xmltwig.com/article/simple_benchmark/</a>).</p>

